                <practice ID="DeceasedFaceQiblah">
                    <explanation>
                        <div>Turning the deceased to face the Qiblah is good, but if this is not done it does not matter. There is no text (nass) which indicates that the deceased should be turned to face the Qiblah. The deceased should be placed in his grave on his right side, with his face towards the Qiblah and his head and legs to the right and left. This is the practice of the Muslims from the time of the Messenger of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) until the present day, and this is how all the graveyards of the Muslims are throughout the world. (al-Mahallaa, 5/173).</div>
                    </explanation>
                    <names>
                        <name language="English">Turning the deceased to face the Qiblah</name>
                    </names>
                    <deontics>suggested</deontics>
                </practice>
                <practice ID="NotSteppingOnGraves">
                    <explanation>
                        <div>In Islam, stepping, walking, or sitting on graves is forbidden out of deep respect for the deceased. A Muslim retains sanctity and dignity after death just as they did in life. Walking or sitting on their resting place is viewed as a severe form of disrespect and harm. Islamic teachings detail several specific reasons for this rule: 1) Respect for the Dead: The Prophet Muhammad stated that stepping on a grave is highly offensive. He strongly warned against it, saying that sitting on a burning hot coal is better than sitting on a grave. 2) Avoiding Harm: According to hadith (recorded sayings of the Prophet), the deceased can feel and be affected by disrespect. Therefore, walking on the soil of the dead causes them unnecessary discomfort. 3) Preventing Damage: Walking or sitting on a grave can cause the soil to sink or damage the grave's marker. 4) Maintaining Sacred Boundaries: Cemeteries are meant to be places of quiet reflection, prayer for the deceased, and remembering one's own mortality. Strict guidelines prevent people from turning graves into areas for casual socializing, walking, or idol worship. In practice, if a visitor needs to reach the other side of a cemetery, they must walk in the paths between the graves rather than directly over them.</div>
                    </explanation>
                    <names>
                        <name language="English">Step, walk or sit on a grave</name>
                    </names>
                    <deontics>forbidden</deontics>
                </practice>
                <practice ID="ShroudingTheDeceased">
                    <explanation>
                        <div>What is required for the deceased in all cases, whether young or old, male or female, is a single sheet that will cover the entire body of the deceased.</div>
                    </explanation>
                    <names>
                        <name language="English">Shrouding the deceased in a piece of cloth</name>
                    </names>
                    <deontics>required</deontics>
